So that's my take.

00:02:33.110 --> 00:02:36.270
So what I'm going to try and
do today is to say the book

00:02:36.270 --> 00:02:39.290
covers a wide variety of things,
and I can't possibly

00:02:39.290 --> 00:02:40.080
cover them all.

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:43.770
What I've tried to do is make
a list of seven myths.

00:02:43.770 --> 00:02:45.540
And I'll go through these,
and if time allows,

00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:46.900
I'll finish them all.

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:50.380
And if it doesn't, I'll
stop wherever I feel.

00:02:50.380 --> 00:02:52.380
But I'll try to go for
about a half an hour.

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:55.870
The first one I want to look at
is whether or not obesity

00:02:55.870 --> 00:02:58.620
is a uniquely modern event.

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:00.930
On the right-hand side of this
screen, there's a book there

00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:04.390
called "The End of Overeating."
It's by David

00:03:04.390 --> 00:03:07.870
Kessler, who is former head of
the FDA in the United States.

00:03:07.870 --> 00:03:10.610
He's a pediatrician, or
was a pediatrician.

00:03:10.610 --> 00:03:13.630
He wrote this in his book.

00:03:13.630 --> 00:03:15.090
For thousands of years,
human weight

00:03:15.090 --> 00:03:17.130
stayed remarkably constant.

00:03:17.130 --> 00:03:19.740
Throughout adulthood we
basically consume no more than

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:21.630
the food we needed to burn.

00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:24.200
People who are overweight stood
apart from the general

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:24.900
population.

00:03:24.900 --> 00:03:26.790
Please remember that, that
they stood apart from the

00:03:26.790 --> 00:03:29.180
general population.

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:31.080
Millions of calories passed
through their bodies, yet with

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:33.690
rare exceptions, our weight
neither rose nor fell.

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:35.460
Rare exceptions.

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:37.825
And everything changed
in the 1980s.

00:03:37.825 --> 00:03:40.890
Now, if Kessler is correct,
then the solution to the

00:03:40.890 --> 00:03:43.170
problem of obesity will
be around the 1980s.

00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:46.290
Something happened in the 1960s
and '70s, or perhaps

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:49.740
into the '80s and maybe '90s,
but he's got a 40, 50, or even

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:52.430
a 60 year period to look
for the solution.

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:55.890
But if he's wrong, as I'm going
to show you, then he's

00:03:55.890 --> 00:03:59.330
going to make a mess
of things.

00:03:59.330 --> 00:04:02.580
I'll go back to Hippocrates.

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:07.620
He wrote, in relation to the
Scythian race, about their

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:10.820
children, that the male
children, until they were old

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:13.390
enough to ride, most of the time
were sitting in wagons,

00:04:13.390 --> 00:04:15.680
and they were talking very
little since they were often

00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:17.680
changing their place
of residence.

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:21.010
And the girls get amazingly
flabby and podgy.

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:23.300
But that's not a rare event.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:26.390
Then one of the greatest writers
of Roman time, Lucius

00:04:26.390 --> 00:04:33.070
Columella, he wrote that, "The
consequence is that ill health

00:04:33.070 --> 00:04:35.420
attends so slothful a manner of
living; for the bodies of

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:38.600
our young men are so flabby and
enervated that death seems

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:41.680
likely to make no
change to them."

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:46.120
Then you go to the city
of Florence, the

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:47.140
city-state of Florence.

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:49.600
And this gentleman, Cornaro,
wrote this book, still

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.920
available on Amazon,
by the way.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:54.040
He wrote it at the age of 94.

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:56.880
And it's pretty important
to read what he says.

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:01.090
"Gluttony kills every year as
great a number as would perish

00:05:01.090 --> 00:05:04.430
during the time of the most
dreadful pestilence or by the

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:09.560
sword or the fire of many
wars." Rare event?

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:10.625
I don't think so.

00:05:10.625 --> 00:05:14.250
And then finally, I'll take you
through to the 18th and

00:05:14.250 --> 00:05:17.860
19th Century to Sir William Wadd
in London, who pointed

00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:19.690
out that the increase of wealth
and refinement of

00:05:19.690 --> 00:05:24.160
modern times, have tended to
banish plague and pestilence.

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:26.260
They have probably introduced
the increased frequency of

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:27.395
corpulence.

00:05:27.395 --> 00:05:30.320
For every one fat person in
Spain or France, there are 100

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:32.860
in England.

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:36.510
Though that's still
the case, I think.

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:39.030
Apologies to my English
colleagues.

00:05:39.030 --> 00:05:42.130
Now, this is a modern
analysis.

00:05:42.130 --> 00:05:44.323
It's interesting to look back in
history, but we really need

00:05:44.323 --> 00:05:46.300
to do some science here.

00:05:46.300 --> 00:05:48.620
This is a study which has
looked at birth cohorts.

00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:51.930
Now, birth cohorts are very
important because you take a

00:05:51.930 --> 00:05:54.110
group of people born in a
certain period, and you follow

00:05:54.110 --> 00:05:56.110
them throughout their lives.

00:05:56.110 --> 00:05:57.930
And then you take another group
born 20 years later.

00:05:57.930 --> 00:05:59.200
You follow them through
their lives.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:04.230
So you take a group in 1880,
1900, 1920, '40, '60, and

00:06:04.230 --> 00:06:05.380
follow them onwards.

00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:08.110
When you put it all together,
you get a picture of the rate

00:06:08.110 --> 00:06:11.390
at which obesity has grown.

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:14.800
In this particular study, you'll
see that from 1880

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:18.850
onwards to 1980, there has
been a linear rise in the

00:06:18.850 --> 00:06:19.720
level of obesity.

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:24.430
It isn't something that has
happened at a flat rate, and

00:06:24.430 --> 00:06:27.190
then suddenly appeared
in 1980.

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:29.850
And if you look at the rate of
change, you'll see that it

00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:31.140
comes in waves.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:33.940
It starts, it slows,
it rises again.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:37.676
I call this the tsunami
of large.

00:06:37.676 --> 00:06:41.900
Now, if you take a different
approach to this-- this is

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:44.130
started from the US military--

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:47.390
and they've looked
at four periods.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:52.770
I've taken the 45-year-old
military personnel there.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:59.120
They showed an increase of 3.4
units of body mass index.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:04.370
The increase was 7% for the
first 30 years, 17% then for

00:07:04.370 --> 00:07:06.050
the next half century.

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:08.070
The next one should
read 17 years.

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:10.790
Half of it took place in that
17 years after the war.

00:07:10.790 --> 00:07:14.725
And then again, it slowed down
in the 1960s to 1990s to only

00:07:14.725 --> 00:07:15.750
a quarter of it.

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:19.200
So again, you have this
undulation and growth.

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:22.790
It's best seen in some studies
in Denmark where they took

00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:26.060
children in the 1930s.

00:07:26.060 --> 00:07:28.380
They had seven, eight, nine,
10, 11-year-olds, and they

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:32.340
followed them on a six-monthly
basis.

00:07:32.340 --> 00:07:35.670
As you can see, there's a slow
gradual rise, and then in the

00:07:35.670 --> 00:07:39.010
1940s, there's a spurt, and then
it drops off again, and

00:07:39.010 --> 00:07:41.012
then there's another
huge spurt.

00:07:41.012 --> 00:07:45.140
And then if you take the Danish
military recruits, just

00:07:45.140 --> 00:07:47.920
start at the end of the Second
World War, again you see the

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:49.110
same pattern--

00:07:49.110 --> 00:07:51.970
a slow rise, a sudden
rise, a dip, and

00:07:51.970 --> 00:07:54.410
then a very fast rise.

00:07:54.410 --> 00:07:57.940
So basically speaking, the
authors of the paper I

00:07:57.940 --> 00:08:00.500
referred to-- and many of them
I could have shown you, but

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:03.040
this was one I particularly
like--

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:05.120
they make two conclusions.

00:08:05.120 --> 00:08:07.780
"Insofar as BMI values have been
increasing gradually over

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:10.780
a century, researchers
attempting to understand the

00:08:10.780 --> 00:08:16.350
causes of the pandemic need to
reflect or focus on the 1980s

00:08:16.350 --> 00:08:19.290
and thereafter to a much longer
run process of social,

00:08:19.290 --> 00:08:22.270
technological, economic, and
cultural change." And then

00:08:22.270 --> 00:08:24.470
they go on to say that "the
finding also implies that the

00:08:24.470 --> 00:08:28.220
policies to attenuate or reverse
the trend would have

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:31.040
to reach deep into the social
fabric and take into

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:33.700
consideration that such
socio-economic forces

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:37.039
generally change at
glacial pace."

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:40.260
So Kessler has it wrong in
thinking that it all happened

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:41.570
in the 1980s.

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:44.500
When he looks around for a
solution, and he will identify

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:47.470
sugar sweetened beverages as one
of the causes, he'll have

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:49.230
gotten it wrong.

00:08:49.230 --> 00:08:53.030
The problem is with obesity is
that I see there are two types

00:08:53.030 --> 00:08:55.350
of people take a scientific
approach to obesity-- the

00:08:55.350 --> 00:08:58.090
solutionists and the analysts.

00:08:58.090 --> 00:08:59.180
I'm an analyst.

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:01.030
I like to find out why.

00:09:01.030 --> 00:09:04.140
The solutionists have an idea
of what to do, and they

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:09.111
justify doing it, such
as taxing sugar.

00:09:09.111 --> 00:09:10.750
Now, this is the second
myth, and it's about

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:12.210
the stigma of obesity.

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:15.940
I'll just go back and say that
I'm going to introduce you to

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:18.760
a number of impressions that
most of you people in this

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:21.270
room will have about
obese people.

00:09:21.270 --> 00:09:22.580
Most of you will have these.

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:24.010
If you're really truthful
to yourself, you'll

00:09:24.010 --> 00:09:25.830
admit yes, you have.

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:28.480
First of all, you'll believe
they're lazy.

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:30.760
Then you'll believe that
they're dishonest, that

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:35.670
they're untidy, untrustworthy,
unreliable, can't manage their

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:42.050
time, have poor self-control,
possibly low IQ, and low

00:09:42.050 --> 00:09:44.380
self-esteem.

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:48.350
Now, that view is widely held
by professionals who look

00:09:48.350 --> 00:09:49.940
after obese people.

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:51.410
It's held by obese people.

00:09:51.410 --> 00:09:54.080
And sadly, it's held
by obese children.

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:57.420
The only thing that's true on
that is the very last one,

00:09:57.420 --> 00:09:59.010
self-esteem.

00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:02.370
Self-esteem doesn't happen
because you are born with bad

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:02.800
self-esteem.

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:05.780
It happens because you got
overweight or a little bit

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:09.190
fat, and you experience
all these prejudices.

00:10:09.190 --> 00:10:11.600
And your self esteem suffers
because of them.

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:13.510
So if there's one thing I'd hope
that would happen after

00:10:13.510 --> 00:10:16.310
this talk, the next time you see
someone that's overweight,

00:10:16.310 --> 00:10:18.130
just be a little bit
sympathetic.

00:10:18.130 --> 00:10:19.890
Just be a little bit
sympathetic.

00:10:19.890 --> 00:10:23.490
So don't always imagine--

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:26.560
I'm going to show you a study
that was repeated twice--

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:28.130
and this was done
with children--

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:31.200
that shows you the scale
of the problem.

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:33.770
Boys were shown drawings of
boys, and girls were shown

00:10:33.770 --> 00:10:34.690
drawings of girls.

00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:36.520
And there were six types.

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:38.050
The first one was healthy,
nothing wrong

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:39.290
with them at all.

00:10:39.290 --> 00:10:41.480
The next one was a
disfigured face.

00:10:41.480 --> 00:10:44.750
The next one was on crutches
with a brace on one leg.

00:10:44.750 --> 00:10:47.130
Then there was one with
a wheelchair--

00:10:47.130 --> 00:10:48.320
one with no left hand.

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:49.000
Sorry--

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.290
one in a wheelchair covered
by a blanket, and

00:10:51.290 --> 00:10:54.020
one that was obese.

00:10:54.020 --> 00:10:56.330
The children were asked to rank
them, who they'd like to

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:58.350
be their friend most.

00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:01.430
Five was the one you didn't
want to be friendly with.

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:03.732
One was you wanted to be
friends with them.

00:11:03.732 --> 00:11:06.110
The results are staggering.

00:11:06.110 --> 00:11:08.560
Nobody wanted to be friends
with the obese children.

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:14.860
They'd rather be friends with
people with all sorts of

00:11:14.860 --> 00:11:20.100
physical impairments, but
not an obese child.

00:11:20.100 --> 00:11:22.190
This is ingrained in children.

00:11:22.190 --> 00:11:25.560
It comes from their parents,
and it's part of the way

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:26.530
society thinks.

00:11:26.530 --> 00:11:30.220
So again, I say to you, the
one thing I want you to do

00:11:30.220 --> 00:11:32.560
when you leave here is be a
little bit considerate.

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:35.620
Here are some people
that are not lazy.

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:38.050
They're not all of the things
you think about them, and

00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:41.520
they're all fat and famous.

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:43.660
Some of them are very
rich and famous.

00:11:47.730 --> 00:11:51.740
The third myth is that obesity
is uniquely caused by the

00:11:51.740 --> 00:11:55.470
environment, and genes have
nothing to do with it.

00:11:55.470 --> 00:11:57.910
I was explaining last night when
I was down in Cork that I

00:11:57.910 --> 00:12:00.300
gave a talk, a lecture once.

00:12:00.300 --> 00:12:03.150
I gave the opening talk to the
World Congress of Public

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:04.270
Health Nutrition.

00:12:04.270 --> 00:12:06.370
They asked me to pick four
topics, any topic

00:12:06.370 --> 00:12:08.015
I liked, hot topics.

00:12:08.015 --> 00:12:09.910
And I picked four,
one of which was

00:12:09.910 --> 00:12:11.880
genetics and obesity.

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:14.390
When I was finished talking,
there was a queue at the

00:12:14.390 --> 00:12:18.440
microphone by eminent public
health nutritionists, each

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:19.970
vying to condemn me.

00:12:19.970 --> 00:12:22.370
How could I possibly say this?

00:12:22.370 --> 00:12:25.580
Genes have not changed
for centuries.

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:27.290
The environment has.

00:12:27.290 --> 00:12:29.060
Therefore, it has to be the
environment, stupid.

00:12:29.060 --> 00:12:31.110
It can't be the genes.

00:12:31.110 --> 00:12:34.360
But I'll show you
that's not true.

00:12:34.360 --> 00:12:37.690
These are two Maasai tribesmen
from Kenya.

00:12:37.690 --> 00:12:40.800
They look after cattle,
and they're nomadic.

00:12:40.800 --> 00:12:43.300
They walk long distances,
so they've

00:12:43.300 --> 00:12:45.430
huge physical activity.

00:12:45.430 --> 00:12:47.400
They eat berries
along the way.

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:48.180
They drink the milk.

00:12:48.180 --> 00:12:50.400
Occasionally, they'll bleed the
cattle, and mix it with

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:52.560
the milk, and drink that.

00:12:52.560 --> 00:12:55.390
They live in a non-obesogenic
environment.

00:12:55.390 --> 00:12:59.360
It's impossible to get fat
as a Maasai warrior.

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:00.230
Impossible.

00:13:00.230 --> 00:13:02.280
You spend so much energy walking
around after your

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:04.620
cattle and eating
so sparsely that

00:13:04.620 --> 00:13:07.320
obesity just ain't possible.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:11.520
This is a food emporium in some
shopping mall or other.

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:14.180
You'd be familiar with them in
airports and what have you.

00:13:14.180 --> 00:13:16.690
And this is an obesogenic
environment.

00:13:16.690 --> 00:13:18.170
This is cheap food.

00:13:18.170 --> 00:13:19.750
This is tasty food.

00:13:19.750 --> 00:13:20.950
This is abundant food.

00:13:20.950 --> 00:13:22.470
It's immediate food.

00:13:22.470 --> 00:13:24.790
It's every cuisine
food you like.

00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:27.352
And this is an obesogenic
environment.

00:13:27.352 --> 00:13:31.540
Now, if I was to take 1,000
Kenyan tribesman and bring

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:32.980
them into this obesogenic

00:13:32.980 --> 00:13:35.740
environment, what would happen?

00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:40.630
Well, I would predict some
would get fat very fast.

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:43.880
I would predict some would
get fat, but very slowly.

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:46.600
Some would get overweight very
fast, and some would get

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:47.540
overweight very slowly.

00:13:47.540 --> 00:13:50.870
Some wouldn't gain
weight at all.

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:52.550
That is the difference.

00:13:52.550 --> 00:13:56.040
The difference in those people
is due to genes.

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:59.760
Put them in the same obesogenic
environment.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:02.890
How they respond to that
environment is genetically

00:14:02.890 --> 00:14:04.050
determined.

00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:06.670
So we live in an obesogenic
environment.

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:09.250
Those of us that gain weight
are gaining weight because

00:14:09.250 --> 00:14:11.550
they have a genetic
predisposition to do so in an

00:14:11.550 --> 00:14:13.170
obesogenic environment.

00:14:13.170 --> 00:14:16.660
Take away the environment,
the genes don't matter.

00:14:16.660 --> 00:14:18.920
Put the environment there, the
genes tell you who's going to

00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:21.173
get top of the league, middle
of the league, or bottom of

00:14:21.173 --> 00:14:22.530
the league.

00:14:22.530 --> 00:14:23.640
So genes matter.

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:25.510
I'll show you some
data on this.

00:14:25.510 --> 00:14:29.500
This is an old study carried out
in the 1970s and forgotten

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:32.430
because it didn't suit public
health nutrition.

00:14:32.430 --> 00:14:35.820
It involved overfeeding twins,
identical twins.

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:38.820
And it also involved
underfeeding identical twins,

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:40.870
all carried out in clinical
conditions.

00:14:40.870 --> 00:14:44.240
In other words, in a ward, where
they were supervised.

00:14:44.240 --> 00:14:47.400
So if I take some
examples here--

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:49.700
let's take the overfeeding
one--

00:14:49.700 --> 00:14:51.510
and we have a green
circle here.

00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:55.000
That dot represents two twins,
two identical twins.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:58.690
If you go down the line to the
change in body weight for twin

00:14:58.690 --> 00:15:01.400
B, it's around about 11 kilos.

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:05.580
And if you go across to the
weight gain on twin A, it's

00:15:05.580 --> 00:15:06.770
about 13 kilos.

00:15:06.770 --> 00:15:09.960
So they've gained more or
less the same weight.

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:11.620
Whereas if you go down
to the red one, they

00:15:11.620 --> 00:15:12.970
resisted weight gain.

00:15:12.970 --> 00:15:15.100
Those two twins resisted weight
gain more or less to

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:16.650
within a kilo of one another.

00:15:16.650 --> 00:15:22.300
And then if you go on to the
period where 1,000 calories

00:15:22.300 --> 00:15:25.100
were taken away from them every
day, they lost weight.

00:15:25.100 --> 00:15:28.080
But look at the ones in green.

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:29.280
They lost very little.

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:30.060
They resisted.

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:31.570
Both twins resisted.

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:35.080
In red, both twins showed
huge weight loss.

00:15:35.080 --> 00:15:38.140
So again, you can see the
genetic component is

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:41.340
determining who responds
to the environment, the

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:44.920
obesogenic or the non-obesogenic
environment.

00:15:44.920 --> 00:15:47.350
Now, the criticism of all of
that was it was carried out in

00:15:47.350 --> 00:15:49.990
the 1970s when we didn't
really have the highly

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:52.750
obesogenic environment
we have today.

00:15:52.750 --> 00:15:55.900
This lady, Jane Wardle, at the
University of London has done

00:15:55.900 --> 00:15:58.430
some incredibly good work with
twins, identical and

00:15:58.430 --> 00:15:59.320
non-identical.

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:01.910
And the thing about identical
and non-identical twins is

00:16:01.910 --> 00:16:05.070
they have a mathematical model
which allows you to work out

00:16:05.070 --> 00:16:08.000
what part of the trait
is heritable.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.400
In the case of obesity, BMI, or
Body Mass Index, or waist

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:14.950
circumference, three quarters,
roughly speaking, is

00:16:14.950 --> 00:16:17.620
accountable for it by
genetic variation.

00:16:17.620 --> 00:16:20.920
That was exactly what they found
in the 1970s, as well.

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:24.440
About, you could say, of the
remainder, a little bit more

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:25.930
than half was in the non-shared

00:16:25.930 --> 00:16:27.060
environment of the children.

00:16:27.060 --> 00:16:29.180
So one child went off to play
hockey, another going to go

00:16:29.180 --> 00:16:31.560
swimming, another going to
drama, another going to do

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:32.840
something else.

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:36.590
And the shared environment
was the whole.

00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:41.470
Now, just to take this a little
bit further, this is a

00:16:41.470 --> 00:16:45.450
longitudinal study
of 428 twins.

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:49.580
They were from 100 obese
families and 100 non-obese.

00:16:49.580 --> 00:16:51.290
Both parents had to
be obese, or both

00:16:51.290 --> 00:16:53.290
parents had to be slim.

00:16:53.290 --> 00:16:56.230
They were followed from four to
11, which is a seven year

00:16:56.230 --> 00:16:58.860
follow up, and they had an
81% retention, which

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:01.770
is very, very good.

00:17:01.770 --> 00:17:06.280
This is obesity at age
four and age 11.

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:11.980
The gray bar represents the
children of slim parents.

00:17:11.980 --> 00:17:15.020
There was no change in the
rate of obesity in those

00:17:15.020 --> 00:17:17.810
children between the
age of four and 11.

00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:21.619
The black bar represents
children both whose parents

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:23.290
were obese.

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:26.720
You can see that there
was a dramatic rise.

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:30.870
Even by age four, there was far
more obesity in those that

00:17:30.870 --> 00:17:35.180
had obese parents, and by age
11, it was through the roof.

00:17:35.180 --> 00:17:37.850
Of course, you might argue that
that's due to the home

00:17:37.850 --> 00:17:38.370
environment.

00:17:38.370 --> 00:17:41.360
But what I've shown you is that
when you study twins,

00:17:41.360 --> 00:17:44.320
identical and non-identical
twins, and you're able to take

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:48.245
away the effect of the home
environment, the environment

00:17:48.245 --> 00:17:53.960
comes out at less than 25%, the
genes accounting for 75%.

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:56.380
I just want to bring in social
class, because this is also

00:17:56.380 --> 00:17:58.320
another myth, so to speak.

00:17:58.320 --> 00:18:00.930
On the bottom, you see that
we've broken this up now into

00:18:00.930 --> 00:18:03.340
two groups.

00:18:03.340 --> 00:18:09.110
We still have the children who
were born of lean parents, and

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:12.570
over the seven year period, they
showed no weight gain.

00:18:12.570 --> 00:18:15.910
Now, we've divided them into two
colors, blue and sort of

00:18:15.910 --> 00:18:19.130
red, and they're different
social classes.

00:18:19.130 --> 00:18:21.320
And social class makes
absolutely and utterly no

00:18:21.320 --> 00:18:23.930
difference if you happen
to have two

00:18:23.930 --> 00:18:26.080
parents that are slim.

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:28.330
But if you go to the top of
this where we have the

00:18:28.330 --> 00:18:32.310
children whose parents were
overweight, then you see that

00:18:32.310 --> 00:18:34.860
social class becomes
important.

00:18:34.860 --> 00:18:39.220
So what you have here is the
same environment, but if you

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:42.000
have the genes to keep you slim,
you'll be slim in that

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:43.110
environment.

00:18:43.110 --> 00:18:45.800
If you have the genes that make
you fat, you'll get fat

00:18:45.800 --> 00:18:46.900
in that environment.

00:18:46.900 --> 00:18:50.110
And that is the reality of it.

00:18:50.110 --> 00:18:52.380
Once again, I say take away the
environment and you take

00:18:52.380 --> 00:18:53.070
away the problem.

00:18:53.070 --> 00:18:54.630
There's nothing to
do with genes.

00:18:54.630 --> 00:18:57.150
But if anyone thinks they can
turn this city into a

00:18:57.150 --> 00:19:01.390
non-obesogenic environment in a
decade, you're a better man

00:19:01.390 --> 00:19:04.310
than I, Gunga Din.

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:06.930
To add to what I've been saying,
this is a recently

00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:10.040
published study of a huge
number, 12,000 twin pairs from

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:12.280
birth to 19 years of age.

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:15.670
Basically speaking, the black
line represents the inherited

00:19:15.670 --> 00:19:17.220
component of obesity.

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:20.570
And the bottom line represents
the environmental side.

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:25.490
At birth, the genetic
side is quite small.

00:19:25.490 --> 00:19:27.500
But by six months,
it's dominant.

00:19:27.500 --> 00:19:30.580
It drops at four or
five years of age.

00:19:30.580 --> 00:19:31.290
I don't know why that is.

00:19:31.290 --> 00:19:32.770
Maybe it's going to school.

00:19:32.770 --> 00:19:33.820
It drops again at seven.

00:19:33.820 --> 00:19:34.580
I don't know why.

00:19:34.580 --> 00:19:38.130
But right through adolescence,
it's the dominant determinant

00:19:38.130 --> 00:19:40.220
of weight in an obese
environment.

00:19:40.220 --> 00:19:42.180
Once again, we have an
obese environment.

00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:44.360
We have winners that win the top
of the league, the bottom

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:46.670
of the league, and the
middle of the league.

00:19:46.670 --> 00:19:47.960
And that's determined
by genetics.

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:49.680
Your position on the league
table is determined by

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:53.210
genetics in an obesogenic
environment.

00:19:53.210 --> 00:19:56.170
Many people think that if
you're talking about the

00:19:56.170 --> 00:20:00.060
genetic control of obesity,
you're talking about metabolic

00:20:00.060 --> 00:20:00.620
parameters.

00:20:00.620 --> 00:20:02.530
You're talking about
how muscle, liver,

00:20:02.530 --> 00:20:04.570
adipose tissue behave.

00:20:04.570 --> 00:20:10.340
But in fact, in man, we have
such a complicated system of

00:20:10.340 --> 00:20:12.570
selecting food, unlike rats,
because we've got a big

00:20:12.570 --> 00:20:17.230
cortex, so we can like things
and dislike things.

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:20.270
It's quite likely that the
genetic variation applies to

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:23.910
behavior as much as it
does to metabolism.

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:28.220
Jane Wardle did this study of
nearly 4,000 or 5,000 twin

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:31.950
pairs, and she was looking at
neophobia, whether children

00:20:31.950 --> 00:20:35.230
like new foods or don't
like new foods.

00:20:35.230 --> 00:20:40.570
What she found was that 78% of
the variability was genetic.

00:20:40.570 --> 00:20:43.170
This is beginning to open
up an explanation of--

00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:44.620
why is genetics important?

00:20:44.620 --> 00:20:47.170
Well, it's only important if it
influences something that

00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:48.960
influences obesity.

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:53.010
She's shown now that neophobia
is strongly inherited, and not

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:55.710
necessarily taught.

00:20:55.710 --> 00:21:01.740
So we're making progress
in that direction.

00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:02.790
OK.

00:21:02.790 --> 00:21:05.240
Moving away from obesity to
things to do with the food

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:09.570
chain, everything that's
synthetic is considered by

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:12.840
people your age, roughly
speaking, as being bad for us.

00:21:12.840 --> 00:21:14.690
And everything that's natural
is considered

00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:15.880
very good for us.

00:21:15.880 --> 00:21:18.560
So let's take a look at that.

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:21.070
It was this chap by the name
of-- he was Swiss--

00:21:21.070 --> 00:21:24.250
Philippus Theophrastus Aureolus
Bombastus von

00:21:24.250 --> 00:21:28.240
Hohenheim And even if I had
his name, I'd change it.

00:21:28.240 --> 00:21:31.020
But he changed it to Paracelsus,
which is equal to

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:34.680
or greater than Celsus, who was
a Roman physician at the

00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:37.630
turn of the millennium, and
quite a famous person.

00:21:37.630 --> 00:21:41.210
So Paracelsus gave us
this one statement.

00:21:41.210 --> 00:21:45.170
"All subjects are poisons and
nothing is without poison,

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:47.090
only the dose permits
something not to be

00:21:47.090 --> 00:21:50.430
poisonous." Swiss Alpine
air injected into your

00:21:50.430 --> 00:21:52.270
veins will kill you.

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:55.740
Pure Kerry water taken wrongly
will kill you.

00:21:55.740 --> 00:21:57.200
Everything is toxic.

00:21:57.200 --> 00:22:00.120
Only the dose and the
circumstances make the

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:02.130
difference.

00:22:02.130 --> 00:22:05.620
So the dose alone makes
the poison.

00:22:05.620 --> 00:22:09.260
If you look at the human food
chain, we have food divided

00:22:09.260 --> 00:22:11.270
nutrients and non-nutrients.

00:22:11.270 --> 00:22:14.630
Nutrients are either added
or they're natural.

00:22:14.630 --> 00:22:19.110
If they're added, they can be
intentionally added, or they

00:22:19.110 --> 00:22:20.800
can be contaminants.

00:22:20.800 --> 00:22:22.890
The naturals are what we
call phytochemicals.

00:22:22.890 --> 00:22:26.170
And I want to talk about
the phytochemicals now.

00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:31.420
Basically speaking, plants
have a lot of colors and

00:22:31.420 --> 00:22:34.240
things like that, and smells,
and tastes, for their benefit,

00:22:34.240 --> 00:22:35.290
not for ours.

00:22:35.290 --> 00:22:38.570
So the fact that the coffee bean
is nice for us, it has

00:22:38.570 --> 00:22:39.650
nothing to do with
the coffee bean.

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:40.820
The coffee bean is
designed for the

00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:42.730
coffee bean's purposes.

00:22:42.730 --> 00:22:45.590
They're not that
philanthropic.

00:22:45.590 --> 00:22:52.840
This is a bird now, pollinating
a flower,

00:22:52.840 --> 00:22:54.480
attracted to it by a scent.

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:56.890
The bees are humming around
the other one.

00:22:56.890 --> 00:22:59.770
There's nothing on the third
flower because it's quite

00:22:59.770 --> 00:23:02.140
toxic, and the birds and
bees don't go near it.

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:04.650
It does its own
cross-fertilization.

00:23:04.650 --> 00:23:06.820
And then you have, on
the bottom left, two

00:23:06.820 --> 00:23:08.570
little shoots appearing.

00:23:08.570 --> 00:23:11.560
Did you ever wonder how a seed
knows when it's springtime?

00:23:14.130 --> 00:23:16.480
How does it know that
it's springtime?

00:23:16.480 --> 00:23:17.960
It detects temperature.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:20.800
So there are compounds in the
seed designed for the seed to

00:23:20.800 --> 00:23:22.120
detect temperature.

00:23:22.120 --> 00:23:24.590
They detect water also.

00:23:24.590 --> 00:23:27.200
And when there's enough water
and the temperature is right,

00:23:27.200 --> 00:23:28.160
they can germinate.

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:30.500
But how do they know
which way to go?

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:32.900
Could they make a mistake
and go down the way?

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:33.620
They could easily.

00:23:33.620 --> 00:23:37.500
So they have oxygen centers
which tell them where the

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:39.440
greatest gradient
of oxygen is.

00:23:39.440 --> 00:23:41.650
So they have all these molecules
in them, helping

00:23:41.650 --> 00:23:44.086
them to solve problems,
including the seedling.

00:23:44.086 --> 00:23:46.340
I put the rabbit there
because plants can't

00:23:46.340 --> 00:23:48.000
run away from you.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:48.780
Plants have to stay there.

00:23:48.780 --> 00:23:52.700
So simple things-- they sting
you or they have thorns.

00:23:52.700 --> 00:23:55.170
But in addition to that, they
have many, many nasty

00:23:55.170 --> 00:23:58.500
chemicals in them, which the
birds, and the bees, and the

00:23:58.500 --> 00:24:00.990
sheep, and the dogs have learned
not to touch because

00:24:00.990 --> 00:24:02.410
they're poisonous.

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:08.150
So the final reason why plants
have these beautiful colors

00:24:08.150 --> 00:24:11.100
and so forth is that we can go
to the toilet and get rid of

00:24:11.100 --> 00:24:12.570
metabolites we don't want.

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:13.210
They can't.

00:24:13.210 --> 00:24:14.490
They have to accumulate them.

00:24:14.490 --> 00:24:16.190
They just save them up.

00:24:16.190 --> 00:24:21.770
And so we eat them, and that's
what makes plants so lovely.

00:24:21.770 --> 00:24:25.190
The color, the taste, the smell,
the texture, the aroma,

00:24:25.190 --> 00:24:28.780
all come from these compounds
that the plant has to

00:24:28.780 --> 00:24:30.570
make its life easy.

