00:28:42.880 --> 00:28:46.910
So if you are going to take
something that's going to kill

00:28:46.910 --> 00:28:52.650
a slug or kill a plant, remember
it's a biocide, not

00:28:52.650 --> 00:28:54.860
sort of water.

00:28:54.860 --> 00:28:56.670
It's designed to kill.

00:28:56.670 --> 00:29:02.620
So don't expect it to be way
down the grade here.

00:29:02.620 --> 00:29:06.070
It's going to have effects on
birds and bees because that's

00:29:06.070 --> 00:29:07.841
what it's supposed to do.

00:29:07.841 --> 00:29:10.280
Now, we look at the
environmental impact, and it's

00:29:10.280 --> 00:29:14.590
argued that organic agriculture
is much more

00:29:14.590 --> 00:29:16.610
friendly to the environment.

00:29:16.610 --> 00:29:19.700
In fact, when the British
government commissioned this

00:29:19.700 --> 00:29:22.940
study, the conclusion
was as follows.

00:29:22.940 --> 00:29:24.690
"There is no clear-cut answer
to the question.

00:29:24.690 --> 00:29:27.360
Which trolley has a lower
environmental impact, the

00:29:27.360 --> 00:29:30.060
organic one or the conventional
one?" Let me just

00:29:30.060 --> 00:29:31.620
explain that.

00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:33.980
In order to grow plants,
you need nitrogen.

00:29:33.980 --> 00:29:36.770
And a conventional farmer
will use chemical

00:29:36.770 --> 00:29:40.100
nitrogen from a plant.

00:29:40.100 --> 00:29:41.560
In this case, there's
two options.

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:43.770
One is to grow a cover crop.

00:29:43.770 --> 00:29:47.070
A cover crop is of a species
of plant that actually

00:29:47.070 --> 00:29:48.800
extracts nitrogen
from the air.

00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:52.800
Clover does it, fixes nitrogen
from the atmosphere.

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:55.780
Then when it's fully grown, you
plow it into the field.

00:29:55.780 --> 00:29:59.570
But what that means is 50% of
your land is not used when

00:29:59.570 --> 00:30:00.980
you're doing this.

00:30:00.980 --> 00:30:02.330
That's inefficient.

00:30:02.330 --> 00:30:04.020
That's not contributing
to the environment.

00:30:04.020 --> 00:30:05.350
You then have to plow it in.

00:30:05.350 --> 00:30:07.410
Plowing is one of the most
environmentally disastrous

00:30:07.410 --> 00:30:09.730
things on the farm.

00:30:09.730 --> 00:30:11.740
On the other hand, you can say,
ah, but we won't do that.

00:30:11.740 --> 00:30:13.690
We'll just use manure.

00:30:13.690 --> 00:30:15.160
Where do you get the manure?

00:30:15.160 --> 00:30:16.365
From the dairy farmer.

00:30:16.365 --> 00:30:17.020
Thank you.

00:30:17.020 --> 00:30:19.930
You got to buy some of his
carbon footprint now because

00:30:19.930 --> 00:30:21.450
you're taking his manure.

00:30:21.450 --> 00:30:24.740
So when you look at the
complexity of organic farming,

00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:27.230
it's not so straightforward
at all.

00:30:27.230 --> 00:30:29.880
Finally, when it comes down to
nutrition, there's been many,

00:30:29.880 --> 00:30:30.650
many reviews.

00:30:30.650 --> 00:30:33.360
This is from the University
of London.

00:30:33.360 --> 00:30:36.940
And basically their conclusion
