bring you the mike.

00:38:08.294 --> 00:38:09.580
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:38:09.580 --> 00:38:11.460
Thank you for the
presentation.

00:38:11.460 --> 00:38:15.320
So far, I've got the question
that recently was subject to a

00:38:15.320 --> 00:38:18.670
discussion between me and
a few other people.

00:38:18.670 --> 00:38:22.190
Is it good, or bad, or
acceptable or neutral to eat

00:38:22.190 --> 00:38:24.802
meat every day?

00:38:24.802 --> 00:38:28.575
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY: Well,
it's acceptable.

00:38:28.575 --> 00:38:29.810
You can get away with it.

00:38:29.810 --> 00:38:30.750
It's not a problem.

00:38:30.750 --> 00:38:32.650
A lot of people don't
like fish.

00:38:32.650 --> 00:38:36.270
My view would be that you
should be able to have a

00:38:36.270 --> 00:38:37.170
little bit of variety.

00:38:37.170 --> 00:38:41.420
So I would be going for poultry,
and I would be

00:38:41.420 --> 00:38:43.200
looking for a little
bit of fish once a

00:38:43.200 --> 00:38:44.520
week or twice a week.

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:50.210
And maybe some dinner with
no meat in it at all.

00:38:50.210 --> 00:38:53.860
AUDIENCE: For the diversity
and enjoyment reasons,

00:38:53.860 --> 00:38:55.960
naturally, you'd do that.

00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:58.980
However, the question is, do you
have any doubts, or have

00:38:58.980 --> 00:39:01.940
you come across any doubts in
your experience that would

00:39:01.940 --> 00:39:08.830
support the health consequences
of either eating

00:39:08.830 --> 00:39:11.800
meat every day, red meat
every day, or not?

00:39:11.800 --> 00:39:15.360
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY: There are
studies which suggest that

00:39:15.360 --> 00:39:19.170
high intakes of red meat might
not be good for cancer of the

00:39:19.170 --> 00:39:22.590
large bowel, but there's
a big botch with this.

00:39:22.590 --> 00:39:24.720
It's not so much the
red meat as the

00:39:24.720 --> 00:39:26.830
doneness of the red meat.

00:39:26.830 --> 00:39:29.933
It's whether you mutilate your
red meat on your barbecue and

00:39:29.933 --> 00:39:31.180
burn it to bits.

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:34.650
Because the things which are
carcinogenic, or potentially

00:39:34.650 --> 00:39:38.670
carcinogenic, are not the
proteins in the meat, but the

00:39:38.670 --> 00:39:41.700
way in which the proteins react
with the sugars to cause

00:39:41.700 --> 00:39:43.240
the browning, and the darkening

00:39:43.240 --> 00:39:44.230
browning, and so forth.

00:39:44.230 --> 00:39:50.390
So the more sort of cooked it
is, the more likely it is to

00:39:50.390 --> 00:39:52.650
be a problem.

00:39:52.650 --> 00:39:56.090
I'm not convinced that the
data is terribly strong.

00:39:56.090 --> 00:39:59.990
But the World Cancer Research
Fund would say that we should

00:39:59.990 --> 00:40:02.330
reduce our intake of red
meat, especially

00:40:02.330 --> 00:40:03.580
well-cooked red meat.

00:40:14.350 --> 00:40:17.780
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering
when you said that basically

00:40:17.780 --> 00:40:19.655
your genetics determine whether
you're going to be

00:40:19.655 --> 00:40:21.720
obese or not, whether you're in
an obesogenic environment

00:40:21.720 --> 00:40:25.590
or not, does that mean that you
kind of think people can't

00:40:25.590 --> 00:40:26.750
make their own choice?

00:40:26.750 --> 00:40:30.090
I mean, like they can make
choices, but is it kind of

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:32.935
predetermined by your genes
and your environment?

00:40:32.935 --> 00:40:39.080
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY: I mean
in a sense, the environment

00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:42.520
will play a role, but the genes
will tell you which one

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:44.910
of us is going to be the weakest
and give into the next

00:40:44.910 --> 00:40:49.180
serving of pudding.

00:40:49.180 --> 00:40:52.830
The big advantage of going down
this road, even though we

00:40:52.830 --> 00:40:57.890
can't change our genes, is that
if we can understand what

00:40:57.890 --> 00:41:01.930
combinations of genes are
responsible for helping people

00:41:01.930 --> 00:41:05.050
to get obese, then we have a
chance of going to people

00:41:05.050 --> 00:41:07.910
early in life and saying, look,
you have a higher than

00:41:07.910 --> 00:41:09.750
average chance of getting
obese for

00:41:09.750 --> 00:41:11.730
the following reasons.

00:41:11.730 --> 00:41:15.780
In your case, it might be that
you're going to be tempted to

00:41:15.780 --> 00:41:16.960
eat a lot of food.

00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:18.340
Others have different
metabolism.

00:41:18.340 --> 00:41:20.380
But we'll begin to know why.

00:41:20.380 --> 00:41:22.730
And, therefore, we'll begin to
target solutions to these

00:41:22.730 --> 00:41:24.220
people earlier on.

00:41:24.220 --> 00:41:25.910
And that's the big advantage.

00:41:25.910 --> 00:41:28.910
Of course, it would be great
if we got rid of the

00:41:28.910 --> 00:41:32.550
obesogenic environment, but it's
never going to happen.

00:41:32.550 --> 00:41:36.330
So it's much better to accept
that this is the way we live,

00:41:36.330 --> 00:41:40.610
good or bad, and to try and
understand how, by a knowledge

00:41:40.610 --> 00:41:44.290
of a person's genomic makeup,
that we can help them

00:41:44.290 --> 00:41:45.630
to deal with it.

00:41:45.630 --> 00:41:48.140
And there is data coming out,
for example, that is

00:41:48.140 --> 00:41:51.880
suggesting that certain genetic
makeups mean that the

00:41:51.880 --> 00:41:56.180
type of diet you use to lose
weight is best determined by

00:41:56.180 --> 00:41:57.000
your genes.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:59.010
So we'll know what's best for
you when you go to lose

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:00.260
weight, as well.

00:42:07.780 --> 00:42:10.730
AUDIENCE: If you can go back
to the carrot example, what

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:13.480
would be exactly, precisely
the difference between an

00:42:13.480 --> 00:42:15.986
organic carrot and a
non-organic carrot?

00:42:15.986 --> 00:42:18.600
Like I read over hear about
a lot of stuff about the

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:20.350
difference, but what is exactly
the difference?

00:42:20.350 --> 00:42:25.390
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY: About
50 pence a kilo.

00:42:25.390 --> 00:42:27.990
And after that, nothing.

00:42:27.990 --> 00:42:29.750
Nothing.

00:42:29.750 --> 00:42:30.640
That's the thing.

00:42:30.640 --> 00:42:36.870
I mean, it is just not possible
to make the carrot

00:42:36.870 --> 00:42:38.120
anything other than
the carrot.

00:42:42.112 --> 00:42:48.000
The mistake that the organic
movement have made is to try

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:51.040
and embellish their approach to
agriculture with advantages

00:42:51.040 --> 00:42:52.570
that don't really apply.

00:42:52.570 --> 00:42:54.790
You don't, for example,
hear vegetarians.

00:42:54.790 --> 00:42:56.420
They just get on with their
lives, vegetarians.

00:42:56.420 --> 00:42:59.310
And they buy vegetarian meals,
and they live a vegetarian

00:42:59.310 --> 00:43:01.670
life, and they don't moan
and groan about it.

00:43:01.670 --> 00:43:05.630
You will see the organic
movement not doing that for a

00:43:05.630 --> 00:43:06.460
very simple reason.

00:43:06.460 --> 00:43:08.420
Absolutely everyone in the
organic movement has a vested

00:43:08.420 --> 00:43:09.630
interest in it.

00:43:09.630 --> 00:43:11.520
They're either farmers, or they
own shops, or they have

00:43:11.520 --> 00:43:12.972
processing units, or
what have you.

00:43:12.972 --> 00:43:15.740
They are in the value of
organic, the business of

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:18.820
organic food, and they want to
pump up its value, and its

00:43:18.820 --> 00:43:20.370
worthiness, and so forth.

00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:21.750
So they will make out that
it's better for the

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:24.520
environment, better for
this, better for that.

00:43:24.520 --> 00:43:26.310
But it's just not true.

00:43:26.310 --> 00:43:28.470
The carrot is simply
the same carrot.

00:43:28.470 --> 00:43:33.790
Because if you take the
transmission of zinc from soil

00:43:33.790 --> 00:43:36.060
into a plant, there's nothing.

00:43:36.060 --> 00:43:37.750
There's no border police in
the carrot saying, sorry.

00:43:37.750 --> 00:43:39.450
You're organic zinc, and
you're inorganic zinc.

00:43:39.450 --> 00:43:40.190
It's a zinc ion.

00:43:40.190 --> 00:43:40.540
That's it.

00:43:40.540 --> 00:43:43.550
Like there's no difference.

00:43:43.550 --> 00:43:45.490
It's impossible to say there's
a difference between the two.

00:43:49.186 --> 00:43:51.640
AUDIENCE: So build on
his question here.

00:43:51.640 --> 00:43:54.530
It's basically one big marketing
scheme that is

00:43:54.530 --> 00:43:58.532
misleading us, and why are we
paying extra for it globally?

00:43:58.532 --> 00:44:02.320
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY: Well,
the way I view this is that

00:44:02.320 --> 00:44:05.800
people who buy organic food know
that they're buying into

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:09.720
a form of agriculture in which
it is laid down exactly what

00:44:09.720 --> 00:44:10.750
can be done.

00:44:10.750 --> 00:44:13.850
So this issue of the horse meat,
maybe if you had organic

00:44:13.850 --> 00:44:16.030
burgers, I don't think
that could happen.

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:19.240
Because they have a far greater
stringency about it.

00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:22.080
So what you're buying into
is a certainty about an

00:44:22.080 --> 00:44:24.155
agricultural production
system.

00:44:24.155 --> 00:44:27.450
Now, if that's all that you
do, that's terrific.

00:44:27.450 --> 00:44:33.450
What I find is that people who
purchase organic food make

00:44:33.450 --> 00:44:37.110
people who don't purchase
organic food feel guilty about

00:44:37.110 --> 00:44:39.100
what they're doing to their
kids by not giving them

00:44:39.100 --> 00:44:40.850
organic food.

00:44:40.850 --> 00:44:42.245
That's when I step in.

00:44:42.245 --> 00:44:45.600
Now, if they want to buy organic
food and say, look, I

00:44:45.600 --> 00:44:48.430
just like the idea of organic
agriculture, I trust organic

00:44:48.430 --> 00:44:51.420
food, I trust their production
system, terrific.

00:44:51.420 --> 00:44:53.830
I have no problems with
that whatsoever.

00:44:53.830 --> 00:44:56.040
Where I do have a problem
is when they start

00:44:56.040 --> 00:44:58.590
to make other people--

00:44:58.590 --> 00:45:02.780
"would you dream of giving
conventionally farmed carrots

00:45:02.780 --> 00:45:04.744
to your baby" kind of thing.

00:45:08.410 --> 00:45:11.030
AUDIENCE: There is a lot of
pressure on moms to breastfeed

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:16.120
now, and I was wondering if it's
true or if it's a myth

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:20.740
that the advantages of
breastfeeding are as many as

00:45:20.740 --> 00:45:23.970
they are advertised when you
go to a baby center.

00:45:23.970 --> 00:45:26.656
Everywhere, they
are everywhere.

00:45:26.656 --> 00:45:28.350
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY: It's
probably the most dangerous

00:45:28.350 --> 00:45:31.120
topic in the world
to comment on.

00:45:31.120 --> 00:45:35.550
But without doubt, without
doubt, breastfeeding has

00:45:35.550 --> 00:45:40.050
enormous advantages, not just
biological advantages, but

00:45:40.050 --> 00:45:42.350
psychological advantages,
as well.

00:45:42.350 --> 00:45:44.450
In the developing world,

00:45:44.450 --> 00:45:47.070
breastfeeding is far more important.

00:45:47.070 --> 00:45:54.290
I mean, really, really, it
really has to be the case in

00:45:54.290 --> 00:45:56.330
the developing world that
children are breastfed

00:45:56.330 --> 00:45:57.660
exclusively for six months.

00:45:57.660 --> 00:45:59.140
Has to be.

00:45:59.140 --> 00:46:03.740
Now, here, in this part of the
world, the reality is that a

00:46:03.740 --> 00:46:07.600
fraction of women cannot
produce enough milk.

00:46:07.600 --> 00:46:12.630
And if you look at dairy cows,
and you look at the output of

00:46:12.630 --> 00:46:16.370
dairy cows, it is distributed
exactly like any other

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:17.370
parameter in life.

00:46:17.370 --> 00:46:18.680
It's bell-shaped.

00:46:18.680 --> 00:46:19.350
Some are good.

00:46:19.350 --> 00:46:20.480
Some of bad.

00:46:20.480 --> 00:46:23.700
They breed up the ones that are
good and get rid of the

00:46:23.700 --> 00:46:25.010
ones that are bad.

00:46:25.010 --> 00:46:26.350
So it's exactly the
same in women.

00:46:26.350 --> 00:46:28.020
Some of them will be excellent
lactators.

00:46:28.020 --> 00:46:29.476
Some will not be.

00:46:29.476 --> 00:46:31.710
Nothing you can do it.

00:46:31.710 --> 00:46:37.410
The problem is that to make
women who can't breastfeed

00:46:37.410 --> 00:46:39.770
feel guilty about using
a bottle is

00:46:39.770 --> 00:46:42.030
shocking, in my view.

00:46:42.030 --> 00:46:46.010
Now, there's another interesting
area about if

00:46:46.010 --> 00:46:50.860
women have the right to choose
or to terminate a pregnancy,

00:46:50.860 --> 00:46:54.450
say, in many countries, surely
they have a right to choose

00:46:54.450 --> 00:46:56.902
not to breastfeed.

00:46:56.902 --> 00:47:00.420
Now, the counterargument to that
is the child is born and

00:47:00.420 --> 00:47:04.140
the child is entitled to the
best food, and therefore, the

00:47:04.140 --> 00:47:06.810
mother should breastfeed.

00:47:06.810 --> 00:47:08.940
There's deep philosophical
issues there.

00:47:08.940 --> 00:47:11.330
But basically speaking, breast
is best, for sure.

00:47:11.330 --> 00:47:14.120
In the developing countries,
it's absolutely essential.

00:47:14.120 --> 00:47:16.760
In our part of the world where
people are busy working and so

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:19.260
forth, sometimes lactation
is not so easy.

00:47:19.260 --> 00:47:21.780
In which case, formula feed
is perfectly acceptable.

00:47:21.780 --> 00:47:23.640
And they should not be made
to feel guilty about it.

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:32.720
AUDIENCE: I just want to ask,
what are your views on diets?

00:47:32.720 --> 00:47:36.060
Because now, people kind of
feel that they go on diet,

00:47:36.060 --> 00:47:37.590
they lose weight
in two months.

00:47:37.590 --> 00:47:40.050
And then they want to eat even
more and gain all of it back

00:47:40.050 --> 00:47:41.160
plus extra.

00:47:41.160 --> 00:47:41.620
This is first.

00:47:41.620 --> 00:47:44.810
And second, if losing weight
can be linked to

00:47:44.810 --> 00:47:46.260
psychological--

00:47:46.260 --> 00:47:49.150
so you want to lose weight,
and you kind of imagine

00:47:49.150 --> 00:47:50.230
yourself losing it.

00:47:50.230 --> 00:47:52.420
And you kind of have bigger
progress than you

00:47:52.420 --> 00:47:54.510
would go on any diet.

00:47:54.510 --> 00:47:56.210
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY: I'm not
too sure about the second part

00:47:56.210 --> 00:47:58.640
of the question, but the first
part, you're absolutely right.

00:47:58.640 --> 00:47:59.750
I mean, look at me.

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:04.840
I've been on more diets than
I care to talk about.

00:48:04.840 --> 00:48:09.980
There is a wonderful statement
from the American Medical

00:48:09.980 --> 00:48:13.840
Association's Council on
Scientific Affairs where they

00:48:13.840 --> 00:48:17.030
talk about the five-year
cure rate for diseases.

00:48:17.030 --> 00:48:21.060
Now basically, the five-year
cure rate for the worst cancer

00:48:21.060 --> 00:48:23.840
is better than the five-year
cure rate for obesity.

00:48:23.840 --> 00:48:26.870
You can take 100 people and
cure them of cancer.

00:48:26.870 --> 00:48:29.320
Come back in five years, and
ask how many are free.

00:48:29.320 --> 00:48:33.630
So if 20 are still free, your
five-year cure rate is 20%.

00:48:33.630 --> 00:48:36.140
Obesity will be worse
than that.

00:48:36.140 --> 00:48:46.730
It is a disastrously difficult
thing to get rid of it easily.

00:48:46.730 --> 00:48:48.150
It's very difficult
to keep it off.

00:48:48.150 --> 00:48:50.130
It's really, really hard.

00:48:50.130 --> 00:48:52.340
It requires lifelong
dedication.

00:48:52.340 --> 00:48:55.430
Take your foot of the tiller
for one minute, and whoop.

00:48:55.430 --> 00:48:56.700
You'll be back.

00:48:56.700 --> 00:48:58.950
So the advice is never
to gain weight.

00:48:58.950 --> 00:49:01.590
My advice, then, to people who
are going to lose weight, is

00:49:01.590 --> 00:49:04.350
don't lose weight until
you really,

00:49:04.350 --> 00:49:05.360
really, really want to.

00:49:05.360 --> 00:49:07.630
And know why you want
to lose weight.

00:49:07.630 --> 00:49:10.430
So for example, if your blood
pressure is fine, if your

00:49:10.430 --> 00:49:12.730
blood glucose is normal, if
all of the other signs are

00:49:12.730 --> 00:49:16.630
perfect, ask yourself, well,
what am I doing it for?

00:49:16.630 --> 00:49:19.010
I would strongly recommend
that nobody starts a diet

00:49:19.010 --> 00:49:21.660
until they have built a little
bit of physical activity into

00:49:21.660 --> 00:49:22.730
their lives.

00:49:22.730 --> 00:49:26.570
Because that is the most
important thing, is to get

00:49:26.570 --> 00:49:28.690
some level of physical activity,
walking for 40

00:49:28.690 --> 00:49:30.520
minutes a day.

00:49:30.520 --> 00:49:32.610
Once you got that in,
only go on a diet if

00:49:32.610 --> 00:49:33.400
you really have to.

00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:36.470
But be prepared for very
slow weight loss.

00:49:36.470 --> 00:49:41.500
And you need to be at it all the
time, watching it all the

00:49:41.500 --> 00:49:47.396
time, because it'll come
back unfortunately.

00:49:47.396 --> 00:49:49.970
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
genetically modified seeds and

00:49:49.970 --> 00:49:51.550
Roundup resistant seeds.

00:49:51.550 --> 00:49:53.810
My understanding is that
Monsanto produced a lot of

00:49:53.810 --> 00:49:55.250
these seeds, and they
also sell Roundup.

00:49:55.250 --> 00:49:58.210
So they've invested
money both ways.

00:49:58.210 --> 00:50:01.496
Do you think there are health
risks to eating food--

00:50:01.496 --> 00:50:05.210
apparently, the corn and wheat
in the US is genetically

00:50:05.210 --> 00:50:07.482
modified to be resistant
to Roundup--

00:50:07.482 --> 00:50:10.530
health risks in eating that
corn as a result of poison

00:50:10.530 --> 00:50:11.865
being sprayed?

00:50:11.865 --> 00:50:13.740
PROFESSOR MIKE GIBNEY:
I can't see any--

00:50:13.740 --> 00:50:17.290
there's no evidence that in the
United States or in South

00:50:17.290 --> 00:50:21.900
America, where genetically
modified foods have either

00:50:21.900 --> 00:50:24.290
been fed to animals or fed
directly to people, that

00:50:24.290 --> 00:50:27.060
there's been any adverse
effect whatsoever.

00:50:27.060 --> 00:50:32.250
And I'd go back to the point
that you have been eating

00:50:32.250 --> 00:50:37.230
atomically mutated plants
all your life.

00:50:37.230 --> 00:50:42.250
They are a blunderbuss compared
to the precision and

00:50:42.250 --> 00:50:47.120
accuracy of genetically
engineered foods.

00:50:47.120 --> 00:50:50.640
It's not always Monsanto.

00:50:50.640 --> 00:50:51.990
It's not always big
corporations.

00:50:51.990 --> 00:50:54.360
Many of the breakthroughs
have come from--

00:50:54.360 --> 00:50:59.440
for example, the University of
Leeds have developed a potato.

00:50:59.440 --> 00:51:03.330
There's a protein on the leaf
of the potato which weevils

00:51:03.330 --> 00:51:04.910
don't like.

00:51:04.910 --> 00:51:07.480
They get sick, and that goes
back to the point that plants

00:51:07.480 --> 00:51:09.320
have to protect themselves.

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:12.090
The weevil doesn't like it.

00:51:12.090 --> 00:51:16.190
Now, if you get the plant tuber,
the potato, none of

00:51:16.190 --> 00:51:19.230
that protein is present,
so the weevil has a

00:51:19.230 --> 00:51:21.300
field day on it.

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:23.200
So what they did at Leeds
University was, they took the

00:51:23.200 --> 00:51:25.150
protein from the leaf.

00:51:25.150 --> 00:51:27.860
They genetically engineered
it into the potato.

00:51:27.860 --> 00:51:31.510
Now, the weevil won't
go near the potato.

00:51:31.510 --> 00:51:33.760
Now, they can only take
that that far.

00:51:33.760 --> 00:51:35.040
They can't take it
beyond that.

00:51:35.040 --> 00:51:37.870
They need the Monsantos, or
someone else with the

00:51:37.870 --> 00:51:39.890
resources, to make it happen.

00:51:39.890 --> 00:51:43.080
It's the same with golden rice,
where they've introduced

00:51:43.080 --> 00:51:47.380
the pre-vitamin A type beta
carotene into this rice, which

00:51:47.380 --> 00:51:51.930
will now go on sale next
year in South Asia.

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:55.470
But for example, the Greenpeace
movement completely

00:51:55.470 --> 00:51:59.710
wrecked the University
of Leeds plants.

00:51:59.710 --> 00:52:05.000
They have to start doing their
work in safer places.

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:09.410
BASF Plant Science, one of the
biggest GM forces in the

00:52:09.410 --> 00:52:12.790
world, have moved
out of Europe.

00:52:12.790 --> 00:52:19.170
So a lot of the technology
will come from labs, and

00:52:19.170 --> 00:52:21.295
they'll have to be taken by big
corporations because no

00:52:21.295 --> 00:52:23.170
one else can do it.

00:52:23.170 --> 00:52:26.330
I can't see any dangers
whatsoever in genetically

00:52:26.330 --> 00:52:29.410
modified foods.

00:52:29.410 --> 00:52:33.450
Every cheese that's on sale
in this country--

00:52:33.450 --> 00:52:35.530
in the old days, they used to
take rennet from a calf's

00:52:35.530 --> 00:52:38.740
stomach and use it to help
curdle the milk.

00:52:38.740 --> 00:52:41.930
And because of the price of
beef, calves weren't being

00:52:41.930 --> 00:52:42.820
killed young.

00:52:42.820 --> 00:52:45.610
They were bringing
them [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:45.610 --> 00:52:47.905
So they got a yeast.

00:52:47.905 --> 00:52:50.830
They genetically engineered the
yeast to produce a protein

00:52:50.830 --> 00:52:54.480
that did exactly what the
calf's stomach did.

00:52:54.480 --> 00:52:56.940
So for the last 30 years, every
piece of cheese that you

00:52:56.940 --> 00:53:01.440
ever ate in your life has been
curdled using genetically

00:53:01.440 --> 00:53:03.540
modified proteins.

00:53:03.540 --> 00:53:06.030
And you're not mooing,
are you?

00:53:06.030 --> 00:53:10.530
So it's very emotional.

00:53:10.530 --> 00:53:12.480
It's been made very emotional.

00:53:12.480 --> 00:53:15.360
And it's quite interesting that
Greenpeace are rowing

00:53:15.360 --> 00:53:17.300
back on this.

00:53:17.300 --> 00:53:21.650
Greenpeace have begun to say
that it's not always bad.

00:53:21.650 --> 00:53:25.040
You will find people saying that
they rubbish genetically

00:53:25.040 --> 00:53:26.450
modified foods on the grounds
that it's not

00:53:26.450 --> 00:53:27.590
going to feed the world.

00:53:27.590 --> 00:53:29.770
Nobody said it was going
to feed the world.

00:53:29.770 --> 00:53:31.895
It might contribute to
it, but it's not

00:53:31.895 --> 00:53:33.373
going to feed the world.

00:53:33.373 --> 00:53:34.340
It might help.

00:53:34.340 --> 00:53:38.590
So I don't see any dangers
in it at all.

